6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Both exchanges calculate funding rates every 8 hours using similar mark-to-index methodologies. OKX uses a weighted average of multiple index sources with tighter spreads during volatile periods. Bitget's rates tend to be more responsive to immediate market sentiment but can experience higher volatility. OKX's portfolio margin system allows for more efficient capital utilization when arbitraging across multiple pairs simultaneously."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lc",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange has better funding rate predictability for arbitrage?","answer":"OKX generally offers more stable and predictable funding rates due to its mature market structure and deeper liquidity. Bitget's rates can be more volatile but potentially more profitable during extreme market conditions."},{"question":"How do the API rate limits compare for automated arbitrage?","answer":"OKX provides higher API rate limits and more sophisticated order types for institutional users. Bitget's API is simpler but has lower throughput, making it less suitable for high-frequency arbitrage strategies."},{"question":"Which platform is better for cross-exchange arbitrage strategies?","answer":"OKX's portfolio margin system and multi-chain wallet integration make it superior for complex arbitrage strategies. Bitget works better as a counterparty exchange due to its competitive rates on newer tokens."},{"question":"How do withdrawal fees affect arbitrage profitability?","answer":"OKX offers more competitive withdrawal fees for major cryptocurrencies and supports more networks. Bitget's withdrawal costs can eat into smaller arbitrage profits, making position sizing more critical."}]}]
